VTulasi, a senior disciple of veteran vidwan Annavarapu Ramaswamy, has cultivated the technique of easy flow of sangatis.V.L.Tulasi Viswanadh of Rajahmundry is a singer with a melodious voice, sound musical sense and abundantpathantaram. Her concert for Sri Sadguru Sangeeta Sabha of Vijayawada at Sri Sivaramakrishna Kshetram Sravana Sadanam was a fine treat for connoisseurs of music.Tulasi, a senior disciple of veteranvidwanAnnavarapu Ramaswamy, has cultivated the technique of easy flow ofsangatis. She gave a fine expression to hermanodlharmamwithout succumbing to the temptation of racing because her voice permits it.Tulasi began the concert with a briskly renderedvarnamin Saraswathi and followed it withNinne BhajanainNata, andNannuganna talliinSindhukannada.After these two items, she presented a brief but satisfying elaboration ofBilaharipreceding thekritiKanugontini.As major items of her concert, Tulasi chosePantuvarali (Ninne near namminanu)andKharaharapriyain which she sumptuously rendered Papanasanam Sivan's compositionJanani.Thealapanawas full of beautiful phrases that brought out the complete portrait of the raga in an excellent manner.Tulasi's brothers Nandakumar (violin) and Jayabhasker (mridangam) proved that they too are accomplished artistes. They gave fine support to the singer.Needless to add, the soulful rendering and the concert as a whole was appreciated by one and all.After a rousingtanifrom Jayabhasker on the mridangam, Tulasi Viswanadh completed her concert with a Ramadaskeertana, a ThyagarajaDivyanama keertanaand a livelythillanaof Dr.Balamuralikrishna inAhir Bhairav.P. SURYA RAOBottom Template Starts
